the Zemarite, and the Hamathite; and afterward were the families of the Canaanite spread abroad. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}The border of the Canaanite was from Zidon, as you go toward Gerar, to Gaza; as you go toward Sodom and Gomorrah and Admah and Zeboiim, to Lasha. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}These are the sons of Ham, after their families, after their tongues, in their lands, in their nations. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}To Shem, the father of all the children of Eber, the elder brother of Japheth, to him also were children born. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}The sons of Shem: Elam, and Asshur, and Arpachshad, and Lud, and Aram. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}The sons of Aram: Uz, and Hul, and Gether, and Mash. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Arpachshad fathered Shelah; and Shelah fathered Eber. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}To Eber were born two sons; the name of the one was Peleg; for in his days was the earth divided; and his brother\uc1\u8217*s name was Joktan. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Joktan fathered Almodad, and Sheleph, and Hazarmaveth, and Jerah; {\super\cf2\fs24 27}and Hadoram, and Uzal, and Diklah; {\super\cf2\fs24 28}and Obal, and Abimael, and Sheba; {\super\cf2\fs24 29}and Ophir, and Havilah, and Jobab; all these were the sons of Joktan. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}Their settlements were from Mesha, as you go toward Sephar, to the mountain of the east. {\super\cf2\fs24 31}These are the sons of Shem, after their families, after their tongues, in their lands, after their nations. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}These are the families of the sons of Noah, after their generations, in their nations; and of these were the nations divided in the earth after the flood. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Babel

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 11}All the inhabitants of the earth had one language and vocabulary; {\super\cf2\fs24 2}and as they travelled westward, they found a broad valley in the land of Shinar, and made their home there.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Then they said one to another, \uc1\u8216*Come, let us make bricks and thoroughly bake them.\uc1\u8217* So they had bricks for stone and asphalt for mortar. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}They said, \uc1\u8216*Come, let us build ourselves a city, and a tower whose top will touch the heavens. We will make a landmark, so that we are not scattered over all the earth.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}But when the {\scaps Lord} came down to see the city and tower that people had built, {\super\cf2\fs24 6}he said, \uc1\u8216*See, they are one people and all have one language. This is only the beginning of their activity, and now nothing that they propose to do will seem too difficult for them. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Come, let us go down there and confuse their language, so that they do not understand each other\uc1\u8217*s speech.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So the {\scaps Lord} scattered them from there over all the earth; and they ceased building the city. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}That is why they named it Babel{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn  Confusion }, for there the {\scaps Lord} confused the language of all the inhabitants of earth and scattered them over the whole world.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Genealogy

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}These are the descendants of Shem. Shem was a hundred years old, and fathered Arpachshad two years after the flood. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Shem lived for five hundred years after he fathered Arpachshad, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Arpachshad lived for five and thirty years, and fathered Shelah. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Arpachshad lived for four hundred and three years after he fathered Shelah, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Shelah lived for thirty years, and fathered Eber. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Shelah lived for four hundred and three years after he fathered Eber, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Eber lived for four and thirty years, and fathered Peleg. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Eber lived for four hundred and thirty years after he fathered Peleg, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Peleg lived for thirty years, and fathered Reu. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Peleg lived for two hundred and nine years after he fathered Reu, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Reu lived for two and thirty years, and fathered Serug. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Reu lived for two hundred and seven years after he fathered Serug, and fathered sons and daughters. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Serug lived for thirty years, and fathered Nahor.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Serug lived for two hundred years after he fathered Nahor, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Nahor lived for nine and twenty years, and fathered Terah. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Nahor lived for a hundred and nineteen years after he fathered Terah, and fathered sons and daughters.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Terah lived for seventy years, and fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 27}Now these are the descendants of Terah. Terah fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran; and Haran fathered Lot. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Haran died in the presence of his father Terah in the land of his birth, in Ur of the Chaldees. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Abram and Nahor took wives: the name of Abram\uc1\u8217*s wife was Sarai; and the name of Nahor\uc1\u8217*s wife, Milcah, the daughter of Haran, the father of Milcah, and the father of Iscah. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}Sarai was barren; she had no child. {\super\cf2\fs24 31}Terah took Abram his son, and Lot the son of Haran, his son\uc1\u8217*s son, and Sarai his daughter-in-law, his son Abram\uc1\u8217*s wife; and they went from Ur of the Chaldees, to go to the land of Canaan; and they nt to Haran, and dwelt there. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}In total, Terah lived for two hundred and five years; and died in Haran. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Abram\uc1\u8217*s Journey

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 12}The {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} said to Abram, \uc1\u8216*Go from your country, your relatives and your father\uc1\u8217*s house to the land that I will show you. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}I will make of you a great nation; and I will surely bless you and make your name famous, so that you will be a blessing. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}I will bless those who bless you, and I will curse those who curse you, and all the families of the earth shall ask for themselves a blessing like your own.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}So Abram set out, as the {\scaps Lord} had commanded him; and Lot went with him. Abram was seventy-five years old when he left Haran. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He took Sarai his wife and Lot his brother\uc1\u8217*s son and all the slaves that they had acquired in Haran, and started for the land of Canaan.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Abram passed through the land to a place called Shechem, to the oak of Moreh. At that time the Canaanites lived there. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The {\scaps Lord} appeared to Abram and said, \uc1\u8216*To your descendants I will give this land.\uc1\u8217* There Abram built an altar to the {\scaps Lord} who had appeared to him. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}From there he moved on to the hill at the east of Bethel and pitched his tent with Bethel on the west and Ai on the east, and there too he built an altar to the {\scaps Lord} and prayed to him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Abram moved on, going from place to place toward the Nagreb. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}There was a famine in the land, so Abram went down to Egypt to live there; because the famine was severe in the land. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}As he was about to enter Egypt, he said to Sarai his wife, \uc1\u8216*You are a beautiful woman; {\super\cf2\fs24 12}so that when the Egyptians see you, they will say, \uc1\u8220*She is his wife\uc1\u8221*; and they will kill me, but let you live. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Say you are my sister, so that everything may go well for me because of you and my life will be spared.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 14}W hen Abram arrived in Egypt, the Egyptians saw that Serai was very beautiful. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}The officials of Pharaoh, when they saw her, praised her to Pharaoh, and she was taken into Pharaoh\uc1\u8217*s household. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}He treated Abram well for her sake. He had sheep, and oxen and donkeys, and male and female slaves, and she-donkeys, and camels. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}But the {\scaps Lord} sent great plagues to Pharaoh and his household because of Sarai, Abram\uc1\u8217*s wife. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Pharaoh called Abram and said, \uc1\u8216*What is this that you have done to me? Why did you not tell me that she was your wife? {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Why did you say, \uc1\u8220*She is my sister,\uc1\u8221* so that I took her to be my wife? Here she is, take her and go.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Pharaoh gave his men orders to send him on his way with his wife and all his possessions. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 13}So Abram and his wife and all his possessions left Egypt and went to the Negreb and Lot went with him. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Abram was now very rich in cattle, in silver, and in gold. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}He journeyed on from the Negreb in stages towards Bethel, to the place where he had earlier pitched his tent between Bethel and Ai {\super\cf2\fs24 4}and had set up the alter to worship the {\scaps Lord}.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Lot, who went with Abram, also had so many flocks and herds and tents {\super\cf2\fs24 6}that the land was not fertile enough to support them both. They had too many animals to live in the same place. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}At that time, the Canaanites and Perizzites were living in the land. So when there was a quarrel between Lot\uc1\u8217*s herdsmen and Abram\uc1\u8217*s herdsmen, {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Abram said to Lot, \uc1\u8216*There should be no quarrels between me and you, or between my herdsmen and yours, because we are relatives. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Is not the whole land before you? Let\uc1\u8217*s separate. If you go to the left, then I will go to the right; or if you go to the right, then I will go to the left.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then Lot looked about and saw that all the plain of the Jordan, as far as Zoar, was well watered everywhere, like a garden of the {\scaps Lord}. (This was before the Lord destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah.) {\super\cf2\fs24 11}So Lot chose for himself all the valley of the Jordan and went on to the east; and they separated from one another. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Abram lived in the land of Canaan and Lot lived in the cities of the plain and moved his tent as far as Sodom. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}(But the men of Sodom were very wicked and sinned against the {\scaps Lord}.)
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}The {\scaps Lord} said to Abram, after Lot had gone away from him, \uc1\u8216*Lift up your eyes and look from the place where you are northward, southward, eastward and westward, {\super\cf2\fs24 15}for all the land that you see I will give to you and to your descendants forever. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}I will make your descendants as many as the dust of the earth, so that if someone could count the dust of the earth, then your descendants could also be counted. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Rise, walk through the length and breadth of the land, for I will give it to you.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Then Abraham moved his tent and lived in the oak grove of Mamre, which is in Hebron, and built there an altar to the {\scaps Lord}. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Victory over the Four Eastern Kings

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 14}I n the days of Amraphel king of Shinar, Arioch king of Ellasar, Chedorlaomer king of Elam, and Tidal king of Goiim, {\super\cf2\fs24 2}they went to war with Bera king of Sodom, and with Birsha king of Gomorrah, Shinab king of Admah, and Shemeber king of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar). {\super\cf2\fs24 3}All these joined forces together in the valley of Siddim (that is, the Dead Sea).
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}For twelve years they had been subject to Chedorlaonier, but in the thirteenth year they had rebelled. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}So in the fourteenth year Chedorlaonier, and the kings that were with him, came and defeated the Rephaim in Ashteroth-Karnaim, the Zuzim in Ham, the Emim in Shaveh-Kiriathaim, {\super\cf2\fs24 6}and the Horites in their hill country of Seir, to El-Paran, which is on the edge of the wilderness. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Then they returned and came to En-Mishpat (that is, Kadesh), and laid waste all the country of the Amalekites, and also the Amorites, who lived in Hazazon-Tamar.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So the king of Sodom went out together with the king of Gomorrah, the king of Admah, the king of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar); and they set themselves in battle array against them in the valley of Siddim; {\super\cf2\fs24 9}against Chedorlaomer king of Elam, Tidal king of Goiim, Amraphel king of Shinar, and Arioch king of Ellasar; four kings against the five. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Now the valley of Siddim is full of bitumen pits; so when the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah fled, they fell into them, but those who remained fled to the mountain. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Then they took all the goods of Sodom and Gomorrah, and all their provisions and went their way. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}They also took Lot, Abram\uc1\u8217*s brother\uc1\u8217*s son, who was living in Sodom, and his goods and departed.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}But one who had escaped came and told Abram the Hebrew. Now he was living by the oaks of Mamre the Amorite, brother of Eshcol, and brother of Aner, and these were supporters of Abram. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}When Abram heard that his kinsman had been taken captive, he led forth his trained men, born in his house, three hundred and eighteen, and pursued as far as Dan. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Then, dividing his band in order to attack the kings by night, he with his servants attacked them, and pursued them to Hobah, which is north of Damascus. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}So he brought back all the goods, and also his kinsman Lot, with his goods, as well as the women and the people.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Then the king of Sodom went out to meet him, after his return from the defeat of Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with him, at the valley of Shaveh (that is, the King\uc1\u8217*s Vale). {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Melchizedek king of Salem also brought out bread and wine; and he was priest of God Most High. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}He blessed him saying:
