\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}When they came to the threshing floor of Atad, which is beyond Jordan, they held there a great and impressive lamentation; and Joseph appointed a period of mourning for his father which lasted seven days. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}When the Canaanites, the inhabitants of the land, saw the mourning at the threshing floor of Atad, they said, \uc1\u8216*This is an impressive mourning among the Egyptians.\uc1\u8217* That is why that place across the Jordan is called, Ebel-Mizraim{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn  Mourning of the Egyptians }.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Then Jacob\uc1\u8217*s sons did for him what he had commanded them: {\super\cf2\fs24 13}they carried him to the land of Canaan and buried him in the cave in the field of Machpelah near Mamre which Abraham bought with the field from Ephron the Hittite to hold as a place of burial. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}After he had buried his father, Joseph and his brothers and all who had gone up with him to bury his father returned to Egypt.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}When Joseph\uc1\u8217*s brothers realised that their father was dead, they said, \uc1\u8216*It may be that Joseph will now hate us and fully punish us for all the evil which we did to him!\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}They sent this message to him: \uc1\u8216*Your father commanded before he died, {\super\cf2\fs24 17}\uc1\u8220*Tell Joseph: Forgive, I beg of you, the wrongdoing and sin of your brothers, for they treated you basely.\uc1\u8221* So now we beg of you forgive the wrongdoing of the servants of your father\uc1\u8217*s God.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
While they were speaking to him, Joseph began to weep, {\super\cf2\fs24 18}his brothers also went and fell down before him and said, \uc1\u8216*See, we are your slaves.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}But Joseph said to them, \uc1\u8216*Do not be afraid; for am I in the place of God? {\super\cf2\fs24 20}You plotted mischief against me, but God intended it for good, in order to accomplish what is now being done, the saving of the lives of many people. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Now therefore do not be afraid; I will provide for you and your little ones.\uc1\u8217* He said this kindly, comforting them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Joseph remained in Egypt with his father\uc1\u8217*s family. He lived a hundred and ten years, {\super\cf2\fs24 23}and he saw Ephraim\uc1\u8217*s great-grandchildren; the children also of Machir the son of Manasseh were borne upon Joseph\uc1\u8217*s knees.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Then Joseph said to his brothers, \uc1\u8216*I am about to die, but God will surely remember you and bring you up from this land to the land which he promised by an oath to Abraham, Isaac and Jacob.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Joseph required an oath of the children of Israel, saying, \uc1\u8216*When God remembers you, as he surely will, then you must carry up my bones from here.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 26}So Joseph died, being a hundred and ten years old; and they embalmed him, and he was put in a coffin in Egypt.
\par}
