\sectd\sect{\header \pard\qr\plain\f0\fs16 1 Samuel (Page \chpgn) \par}{\pard \pagebb
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs72 The First Book of Samuel
 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs48 Samuel

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Samuel\uc1\u8217*s Birth

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 1}Now there was a certain man of Ramah, a Zuphite of the hill country of Ephraim, and his name was Elkanah the son of Jeroham, the son of Elihu, the son of Tohu, the son of Zuph, an Ephraimite. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}He had two wives: the name of the one was Hannah, and the name of the other Peninnah. Peninnah had children, but Hannah had none. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}This man used to go up from his city year by year to worship and to sacrifice to the {\scaps Lord} of armies in Shiloh. Eli and his two sons, Hophni and Phinehas, were priests to the {\scaps Lord} there. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}It came to pass on one occasion that Elkanah sacrificed. Now he used to give portions to Peninnah his wife and to all her sons and daughters, {\super\cf2\fs24 5}but to Hannah he used to give a double portion because he loved her. But the {\scaps Lord} had shut up her womb. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Her rival used to vex her bitterly in order to make her angry, because the {\scaps Lord} had shut up her womb. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}This happened year after year, as often as she went up to the house of the {\scaps Lord}, she used to vex her; therefore she wept and would not eat. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}But Elkanah her husband said to her, \uc1\u8216*Hannah, why do you weep and not eat, and why is your heart sad? Am not I better to you than ten sons?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

