 {\cf1 30}Now when David and his men  on the third day, the Amalekites had made a raid on the South Country and on Ziklag, and had attacked Ziklag and burnt it down, {\super\cf2\fs24 2}and had carried away captive the women and all who were in it, both small and great. They did not kill anyone, but carried them off and went on their way. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}When David and his men came to the city, they found it burned down, and their wives and their sons and their daughters taken captive. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Then David and the people who were with him wept aloud until they were no longer able to weep. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}David\uc1\u8217*s two wives had been take captive, Ahinoam the Jezreelite, and Abigail the wife of Nabal the Carmelite. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}David was in great trouble, for the people spoke of stoning him, because the spirit of all the people was embittered, each for his sons and for his daughters.
