 {\cf1 52}Zedekiah, who was twenty-one years of age when he{\super\cf2\fs24 1}came to the throne, reigned for eleven years in Jerusalem.His mother\uc1\u8217*s name was Hamutal, a daughter of {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Jeremiah of Libnah. His actions were offensive to {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Jehovah was so angry with Jerusalem and Judah thatHe cast them out of His sight; and Zedekiah revoltedagainst the king of Babylon.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 4}On the tenth day of the tenth month of the ninthyear of his reign Nebuchadrezzar, king of Babylon,came with all his forces to storm Jerusalem. Theypitched their camp against it, and surrounded it with {\super\cf2\fs24 5}a siege-wall; so the city was undersiege till the eleventh {\super\cf2\fs24 6}year of king Zedekiah. In the ninth day of the fourthmonth \uc1\u8211* the famine in the city being so severe that {\super\cf2\fs24 7}there was no bread for the people of the land \uc1\u8211* abreach was made in the city, and all the soldiers tookto flight, leaving the city during the night by way of thegate between the two walls by the royal garden\uc1\u8211*the city being surrounded by the Chaldeans \uc1\u8211* and they {\super\cf2\fs24 8}made for the Jordan valley. But the Chaldean armypursued the king and overtook him in the steppes ofJericho, all his own army having left him and scattered. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}They seized the king and brought him to the king ofBabylon who was at Riblah in the district of Hamath; {\super\cf2\fs24 10}and he pronounced judgment upon him. At Riblahthe king of Babylon slew the sons of Zedekiah beforehis eyes, and all the princes of Judah did he also slay; {\super\cf2\fs24 11}he then put out Zedekiah\uc1\u8217*s eyes, and having loaded himwith chains, he carried him to Babylon, where he kepthim in the House of Discipline till the day of his death.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}On the tenth day of the fifth month of the nineteenthyear of king Nebuchadrezzar, king of Babylon,Nebuzaradan the commander of the guard, one of theministers of the king of Babylon, entered Jerusalem; {\super\cf2\fs24 13}and he proceeded to burn the Temple, the palace, and {\super\cf2\fs24 14}indeed every house in Jerusalem. All the walls thatencircled Jerusalem were demolished by the Chaldeanforces that were under the commander of the guard. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}The rest of the people left in the city, and the deserterswho had gone over the king of Babylon, and thosethat were left of the artificers, were carried into exile by {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Nebuzaradan the commander of the guard. Some ofthe poorest of the country people were left by Nebuzar-adan, the commander of the guard, to act as vine-dressers and ploughmen.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}The bronze pillars of the Temple, and the stands,and the bronze sea that was in the Temple, were brokenin pieces by the Chaldeans, and all the bronze of them {\super\cf2\fs24 18}was taken to Babylon. They also took the pots andthe shovels and the snuffers and the basons and thepans and all the bronze vessels used in the (Temple) {\super\cf2\fs24 19}service. The goblets and the snuff-dishes (for thelamps) and the basons and the pots and the lamp-stands and the pans and the libation bowls \uc1\u8211* whateverwas of gold or silver respectively \uc1\u8211* were removed by the {\super\cf2\fs24 20}commander of the guard: \uc1\u8211* the pillars, two; the seaone; and the bronze bulls that supported the sea,twelve; and the stands which King Solomon hadmade for the Temple, ten; \uc1\u8211* vessels the mass of whose {\super\cf2\fs24 21}bronze was beyond weight. Each of the pillars wastwenty-seven feet in height, eighteen feet in circum-ference, three inches in thickness, and hollow within. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}It was surmounted by a bronze capital, seven feet and ahalf in height, round which ran network and pome-granates of bronze throughout; the (network and) {\super\cf2\fs24 23}pomogranate adorment of both pillars was alike. Onthe network round about there were a hundred pome-granates in all, of which ninety-six were visible.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 24}The commander of the guard also took Seraiah thechief priest, and Zephaniah the second priest, and the {\super\cf2\fs24 25}three keepers of the threshold. He took also from thecity a eunuch who had charge of the soldiers, and sevenof the King\uc1\u8217*s Privy Councillors who were found inthe city, and the secretary of the commander-in-chief,who kept the army register, and sixty of the people of {\super\cf2\fs24 26}the land whom he found within the city. Havingseized them, Nebuzaradan, the commander of the guard,brought them to Riblah to the king of Babylon; {\super\cf2\fs24 27}and the king of Babylon put them to death at Riblahin the district of Hamath. Thus was Judah carriedfrom her own land into exile.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 28}These are the people whom Nebuchadrezzar carriedinto exile; in the seventeenth year (of his reign) {\super\cf2\fs24 29}three thousand and twenty-three Jews; in the eight-eenth year of Nebuchadrezzar, eight hundred and {\super\cf2\fs24 30}thirty-two persons from Jerusalem; in the twenty-third year of Nebuchadrezzar Nebuzaradan thecommander of the guard carried seven hundred andforty-five Jews into exile: \uc1\u8211* in all, four thousandsix hundred.
\par}

