 {\cf1 1}This message from the {\scaps {\super\cf2\fs24 1}Lord} came to Jonah, the son of Amittai: {\super\cf2\fs24 2}\uc1\u8216*Arise, go to that great city, Nineveh, and preach against it; for their wickedness is known to me.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 3}But Jonah started to flee to Tarshish from the presence of the {\scaps Lord}. He went down to Joppa and found a ship going to Tarshish. So he paid the fare and went aboard to go with them to Tarshish from the presence of the {\scaps Lord}. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}But the {\scaps Lord} made a furious wind blow over the sea, and there was such a great storm that the ship was in danger of breaking to pieces. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}The sailors were terrified and each cried for help to his own god. They threw the ship\uc1\u8217*s cargo into the sea to make the ship lighter. Meanwhile Jonah had gone down into the bottom of the ship and lay fast asleep. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The captain of the ship went and said to him, \uc1\u8216*How can you sleep? Call on your god; perhaps that god will think of us, so that we may not be lost.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}The sailors said to one another, \uc1\u8216*Come, let us cast lots to discover on whose account this evil has come upon us.\uc1\u8217* So they cast lots, and the lot indicated Jonah. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}So they said to him, \uc1\u8216*Are you to blame for this? Tell us, what is your business, and where do you come from? What is your country and to what people do you belong?\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 9}He replied, \uc1\u8216*I am a Hebrew, and a worshipper of the {\scaps Lord}, the God of heaven, who made the sea and the dry land.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Then the men were greatly frightened and said to him, \uc1\u8216*What have you done?\uc1\u8217* For they knew that he was fleeing from the presence of the {\scaps Lord}, because he had told them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Then they said to him, \uc1\u8216*What should we do to you, to make the sea calm for us?\uc1\u8217* For the sea grew more and more stormy. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}He said to them, \uc1\u8216*Take me up and throw me into the sea, and the sea will be calm for you, for I know that it is because of me this fierce storm has overtaken you.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}But instead the men rowed hard to get back to the land; they could not, however, for the sea grew more and more stormy ahead. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}So they cried to the {\scaps Lord} and said, \uc1\u8216*We beg you, {\scaps Lord}, we beg you, don\uc1\u8217*t let us die for this man\uc1\u8217*s life, and don\uc1\u8217*t let us be guilty of shedding innocent blood, for you are the {\scaps Lord}; you have done as it pleases you.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 15}And they took up Jonah, and threw him into the sea; and the sea became calm. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Then the men greatly feared the {\scaps Lord}, and they offered a sacrifice and made vows to him.
