{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}\uc1\u8216*Do not store up treasures for yourselves on earth, where moth and rust destroy, and where thieves break in and steal. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}But store up treasures for yourselves in heaven, where neither moth nor rust destroys, and where thieves do not break in or steal. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}For where your treasure is, there will your heart be also. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}The lamp of the body is the eye. If your eye is unclouded, your whole body will be lit up; {\super\cf2\fs24 23}but, if your eye is diseased, your whole body will be darkened. And, if the inner light is darkness, how intense must that darkness be! {\super\cf2\fs24 24}No one can serve two masters, for either they will hate one and love the other, or else they will attach themselves to one and despise the other. You cannot serve both God and Money.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 25}\uc1\u8216*This is why I say to you, Do not be anxious about your life \uc1\u8211* what you can get to eat or drink, or about your body \uc1\u8211* what you can get to wear. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothing? {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Look at the wild birds \uc1\u8211* they neither sow, nor reap, nor gather into barns; and yet your heavenly Father feeds them! Aren\uc1\u8217*t you more precious than they? {\super\cf2\fs24 27}But which of you, by being anxious, can prolong their life a single moment? {\super\cf2\fs24 28}And why be anxious about clothing? Study the wild lilies, and how they grow. They neither toil nor spin; {\super\cf2\fs24 29}yet I tell you that even Solomon in all his splendour was not robed like one of these. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}If God so clothes even the grass of the field, which is living today and tomorrow will be thrown into the oven, won\uc1\u8217*t he much more clothe you, you of little faith? {\super\cf2\fs24 31}Do not then ask anxiously \uc1\u8220*What can we get to eat?\uc1\u8221* or \uc1\u8220*What can we get to drink?\uc1\u8221* or \uc1\u8220*What can we get to wear?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 32}All these are the things for which the nations are seeking, and your heavenly Father knows that you need them all. {\super\cf2\fs24 33}But first seek his kingdom and the righteousness that he requires, and then all these things will be added for you. {\super\cf2\fs24 34}Therefore do not be anxious about tomorrow, for tomorrow will bring its own anxieties. Every day has trouble enough of its own. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 7}\uc1\u8216*Do not judge and you will not be judged. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}For, just as you judge others, you will yourselves be judged, and the standard that you use will be used for you. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Why do you look at the speck of sawdust in your friend\uc1\u8217*s eye, while you pay no attention at all to the plank of wood in yours? {\super\cf2\fs24 4}How will you say to your friend \uc1\u8220*Let me take out the speck from your eye,\uc1\u8221* when all the time there is a plank in your own? {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Hypocrite! Take out the plank from your own eye first, and then you will see clearly how to take out the speck from your friend\uc1\u8217*s.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}\uc1\u8216*Do not give what is sacred to dogs; they will turn and maul you. Do not throw your pearls before pigs; they will trample them underfoot. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Ask, and it will be given to you; search, and you will find; knock, and the door will be opened to you. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}For the person who asks receives, the person who searches finds, and to the door will be opened to the person who knocks. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Who among you, when their child asks them for bread, will give them a stone, {\super\cf2\fs24 10}or when they ask for a fish, will give them a snake? {\super\cf2\fs24 11}If you, then, wicked though you are, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father who is in heaven give what is good to those who ask him!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}\uc1\u8216*Do to others whatever you would wish them to do to you; for that is the teaching of both the Law and the prophets. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Go in by the small gate. The road that leads to destruction is broad and spacious, and many go in by it. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}For the gate is small, and the road narrow, that leads to life, and there are few who find it.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}\uc1\u8216*Beware of false teachers \uc1\u8211* people who come to you in the guise of sheep, but at heart they are ravenous wolves. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}By the fruit of their lives you will know them. Do people pick grapes from thorn bushes, or figs from thistles? {\super\cf2\fs24 17}So, too, every sound tree bears good fruit, while a worthless tree bears bad fruit. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}A sound tree cannot produce bad fruit, nor can a worthless tree bear good fruit. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Every tree that fails to bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}So it is by the fruit of their lives that you will know such people. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Not everyone who says to me \uc1\u8220*Master! Master!\uc1\u8221* will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only he who does the will of my Father who is in heaven. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}On \uc1\u8220*that day\uc1\u8221* many will say to me \uc1\u8220*Master, Master, was not it in your name that we taught, and in your name that we drove out demons, and in your name that we did many miracles?\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 23}And then I will say to them plainly \uc1\u8220*I never knew you. Go from my presence, you who live in sin.\uc1\u8221*
