 {\super\cf2\fs24 28}Afterwards, knowing that everything was now finished, Jesus said, in fulfilment of the words of scripture, \uc1\u8216*I am thirsty.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 29}There was a bowl standing there full of common wine; so they put a sponge soaked in the wine on the end of a hyssop-stalk, and held it up to his mouth. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}When Jesus had received the wine, he exclaimed, \uc1\u8216*All is finished!\uc1\u8217* Then, bowing his head, he resigned his spirit to God. {\super\cf2\fs24 31}It was the Preparation day, and so, to prevent the bodies from remaining on the crosses during the Sabbath (for that Sabbath was a great day), the Jews asked Pilate to have the legs broken and the bodies removed. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}Accordingly the soldiers came and broke the legs of the first man, and then those of the other who had been crucified with Jesus; {\super\cf2\fs24 33}but, on coming to him, when they saw that he was already dead, they did not break his legs. {\super\cf2\fs24 34}One of the soldiers, however, pierced his side with a spear, and blood and water immediately flowed from it. {\super\cf2\fs24 35}This is the statement of one who actually saw it \uc1\u8211* and his statement may be relied on, and he knows that he is speaking the truth \uc1\u8211* and it is given in order that you also may be convinced. {\super\cf2\fs24 36}For all this happened in fulfilment of the words of scripture \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Not one of its bones will be broken.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 37}And there is another passage which says \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*They will look on him whom they pierced.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 38}After this, Joseph of Ramah, a disciple of Jesus \uc1\u8211* but a secret one, owing to his fear of the religious authorities \uc1\u8211* begged Pilate\uc1\u8217*s permission to remove the body of Jesus. Pilate gave him leave; so Joseph went and removed the body. {\super\cf2\fs24 39}Nicodemus, too \uc1\u8211* the man who had formerly visited Jesus by night \uc1\u8211* came with a roll of myrrh and aloes, weighing nearly a hundred pounds. {\super\cf2\fs24 40}They took the body of Jesus, and wound it in linen with the spices, according to the Jewish mode of burial. {\super\cf2\fs24 41}At the place where Jesus had been crucified there was a garden, and in the garden a newly made tomb in which no one had ever been laid. {\super\cf2\fs24 42}And so, because of its being the Preparation day, and as the tomb was close at hand, they laid Jesus there. 
