{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*He scattered broadcast, he gave to the poor; His righteousness continues for ever.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}And he who supplies seed to the sower, and bread for eating, will supply you with seed, and cause it to increase, and will multiply the fruits of your righteousness). {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Rich in all things yourselves, you will be able to show liberality to all, which, with our help, will cause thanksgiving to be offered to God. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}For the rendering of a public service such as this, not only relieves the needs of your fellow Christians, but also results in the offering to God of many a thanksgiving. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Through the evidence afforded by the service rendered, you cause people to praise God for your fidelity to your profession of faith in the good news of the Christ, as well as for the liberality of your contributions for them and for all others. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And they also, in their prayers for you, express their longing to see you, because of the surpassing love of God displayed toward you. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}All thanks to God for his inestimable gift! 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Apostle\uc1\u8217*s Claims and Authority

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 10}Now, I, Paul, make a personal appeal to you by the meekness and gentleness of the Christ \uc1\u8211* I who, \uc1\u8216*in your presence, am humble in my bearing towards you, but, when absent, am bold in my language to you\uc1\u8217* \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 2}I implore you not to drive me to \uc1\u8216*show my boldness,\uc1\u8217* when I do come, by the confident tone which I expect to have to adopt towards some of you, who are expecting to find us influenced in our conduct by earthly motives. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}For, though we live an earthly life, we do not wage an earthly war. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}The weapons for our warfare are not earthly, but, under God, are powerful enough to pull down strongholds. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}We are engaged in confuting arguments and pulling down every barrier raised against the knowledge of God. We are taking captive every hostile thought, to bring it into submission to the Christ, {\super\cf2\fs24 6}and are fully prepared to punish every act of rebellion, when once your submission is complete. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}You look at the outward appearance of things! Let anyone, who is confident that he belongs to Christ, reflect, for himself, again on the fact \uc1\u8211* that we belong to Christ no less than he does. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Even if I boast extravagantly about our authority \uc1\u8211* which the Lord gave us for building up your faith and not for overthrowing it \uc1\u8211* still I have no reason to be ashamed. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}I say this so that it doesn\uc1\u8217*t seem as if I am trying to overawe you by my letters. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}For people say \uc1\u8216*His letters are impressive and vigorous, but his personal appearance is insignificant and his speaking contemptible.\uc1\u8217* {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Let such a person be assured of this \uc1\u8211* that our words in our letters show us to be, when absent, just what our deeds will show us to be, when present. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}We have not indeed the audacity to class or compare ourselves with some of those who indulge in self-commendation! But, when such persons measure themselves by themselves, and compare themselves with themselves, they show a want of wisdom. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}We, however, will not give way to unlimited boasting, but will confine ourselves to the limits of the sphere to which God limited us, when he permitted us to come as far as Corinth. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}For it is not the case, as it would be if we were not in the habit of coming to you, that we are exceeding our bounds! Why, we were the very first to reach you with the good news of the Christ! {\super\cf2\fs24 15}Our boasting, therefore, is not unlimited, nor does it extend to the labours of others; but our hope is that, as your faith grows, our influence among you may be very greatly increased \uc1\u8211* though still confined to our sphere \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 16}So that we will be able to tell the good news in the districts beyond you, without trespassing on the sphere assigned to others, or boasting of what has been already done. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Let anyone who boasts make their boast of the Lord. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}For it is not those who commend themselves that stand the test, but those who are commended by the Lord. 
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 11}I could wish that you would tolerate a little folly in me! But indeed you do tolerate me. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}I am jealous over you with the jealousy of God. For I engaged you to one husband so that I might present you to the Christ a pure bride. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Yet I fear that it may turn out that, just as the snake by his craftiness deceived Eve, so your minds may have lost the loyalty and purity due from you to the Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}For, if some newcomer is proclaiming a Jesus other than him whom we proclaimed, or if you are receiving a Spirit different from the Spirit which you received, or a good news different from that which you welcomed, then you are marvellously tolerant! {\super\cf2\fs24 5}I do not regard myself as in any way inferior to the most eminent apostles! {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Though I am no trained orator, yet I am not without knowledge; indeed we made this perfectly clear to you in every way.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Perhaps you say that I did wrong in humbling myself that you might be exalted \uc1\u8211* I mean because I told you God\uc1\u8217*s good news without payment. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}I robbed other churches by taking pay from them, so that I might serve you! {\super\cf2\fs24 9}And, when I was with you in need, I did not become a burden to any of you; for our friends, on coming from Macedonia, supplied my needs. I kept myself, and will keep myself from being an expense to you in any way. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}As surely as I know anything of the truth of Christ, this boast, as far as I am concerned, will not be stopped in any part of Greece. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Why? Because I do not love you? God knows that I do!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}What I am doing now I will continue to do in order to cut away the ground from under those who are wishing for some ground for attacking me, so that as regards the thing of which they boast they may appear in their true characters, just as we do. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Such people are false apostles, treacherous workers, disguising themselves as apostles of Christ! {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And no wonder; for even Satan disguises himself as an angel of light. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}It is not surprising, therefore, if his servants also disguise themselves as servants of righteousness. But their end will be in accordance with their actions.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}I say again \uc1\u8211* Let no one think me a fool! Yet, if you do, at least welcome me as you would a fool, so that I, too may indulge in a little boasting. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}When I speak like this, I am not speaking as the Master would, but as a fool might, in boasting so confidently. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}As so many are boasting of earthly things, I, too, will boast. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}For all your cleverness, you tolerate fools willingly enough! {\super\cf2\fs24 20}You tolerate a person even when they enslave you, when they plunder you, when they get you into their power, when they put on airs of superiority, when they strike you in the face! {\super\cf2\fs24 21}I admit, to my shame, that we have been weak. But whatever the subject on which others are not afraid to boast \uc1\u8211* though it is foolish to say so \uc1\u8211* I am not afraid either! {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Are they Hebrews? So am I! Are they Israelites? So am I! Are they descendants of Abraham? So am I! {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Are they \uc1\u8220*Servants of Christ\uc1\u8221*? Though it is madness to talk like this, I am more so than they! I have had more of toil, more of imprisonment! I have been flogged times without number. I have been often at death\uc1\u8217*s door. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Five times I received at the hands of my own people forty lashes, all but one. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Three times I was beaten with rods. Once I was stoned. Three times I was shipwrecked. I have spent a whole day and night in the deep. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}My journeys have been many. I have been through dangers from rivers, dangers from robbers, dangers from my own people, dangers from the Gentiles, dangers in towns, dangers in the country, dangers on the sea, dangers among people pretending to be followers of the Lord. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}I have been through toil and hardship. I have passed many a sleepless night; I have endured hunger and thirst; I have often been without food; I have known cold and nakedness. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}And, not to speak of other things, there is my daily burden of anxiety about all the churches. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Who is weak without my being weak? Who is led astray without my burning with indignation? {\super\cf2\fs24 30}If I must boast, I will boast of things which show my weakness! {\super\cf2\fs24 31}The God and Father of the Lord Jesus \uc1\u8211* he who is for ever blessed \uc1\u8211* knows that I am speaking the truth. {\super\cf2\fs24 32}When I was in Damascus, the Governor under King Aretas had the gates of that city guarded, so as to arrest me, {\super\cf2\fs24 33}but I was let down in a basket through a window in the wall, and so escaped his hands. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 12}I must boast! It is unprofitable; but I will pass to visions and revelations given by the Lord. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}I know a man in union with Christ, who, fourteen years ago \uc1\u8211* whether in the body or out of the body I do not know; God knows \uc1\u8211* was caught up (this man of whom I am speaking) to the third heaven. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}And I know that this man \uc1\u8211* whether in the body or separated from the body I do not know; God knows \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Was caught up into Paradise, and heard unspeakable things of which no human being may tell. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}About such a man I will boast, but about myself I will not boast except as regards my weaknesses. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Yet if I choose to boast, I will not be a fool; for I will be speaking no more than the truth. But I refrain, in case anyone should credit me with more than he can see in me or hear from me, and because of the marvellous character of the revelations. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}It was for this reason, and to prevent my thinking too highly of myself, that a thorn was sent to pierce my flesh \uc1\u8211* an instrument of Satan to discipline me \uc1\u8211* so that I should not think too highly of myself. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}About this I three times entreated the Lord, praying that it might leave me. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But his reply has been \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*My help is enough for you; for my strength attains its perfection in the midst of weakness.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
Most gladly, then, will I boast all the more of my weaknesses, so that the strength of the Christ may overshadow me. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}That is why I delight in weakness, ill treatment, hardship, persecution, and difficulties, when borne for Christ. For, when I am weak, then it is that I am strong!
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Conclusion

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}I have been \uc1\u8216*playing the fool!\uc1\u8217* It is you who drove me to it. For it is you who ought to have been commending me! Although I am nobody, in no respect did I prove inferior to the most eminent apostles. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}The marks of the true apostle were exhibited among you in constant endurance, as well as by signs, by marvels, and by miracles. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}In what respect, I ask, were you treated worse than the other churches, unless it was that, for my part, I refused to become a burden to you? Forgive me the wrong I did to you!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Remember, this is the third time that I have made every preparation to come to see you, and I will refuse to be a burden to you; I want, not your money, but you. It is not the duty of children to put by for their parents, but of parents to put by for their children. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}For my part, I will most gladly spend, and be spent, for your welfare. Can it be that the more intensely I love you the less I am to be loved? {\super\cf2\fs24 16}You will admit that I was not a burden to you but you say that I was \uc1\u8216*crafty\uc1\u8217* and caught you \uc1\u8216*by a trick\uc1\u8217*! {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Do you assert that I took advantage of you through any of those whom I have sent to you? {\super\cf2\fs24 18}I urged Titus to go, and I sent another follower with him. Did Titus take any advantage of you? Didn\uc1\u8217*t we live in the same Spirit, and tread in the same footsteps?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}Have you all this time been fancying that it is to you that we are making our defence? No, it is in the sight of God, and in union with Christ, that we are speaking. And all this, dear friends, is to build up your characters; {\super\cf2\fs24 20}for I am afraid that perhaps, when I come, I may find that you are not what I want you to be, and, on the other hand, that you may find that I am what you do not want me to be. I am afraid that I may find quarrelling, jealousy, ill feeling, rivalry, slandering, backbiting, self-assertion, and disorder. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}I am afraid that, on my next visit, my God may humble me in regard to you, and that I may have to mourn over many who have long been sinning, and have not repented of the impurity, immorality, and sensuality, in which they have indulged. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 13}For the third time I am coming to see you. By the word of two or three witnesses each statement will be established. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}I have said it, and I say it again before I come, just as if I were with you on my second visit, though for the moment absent, I say to those who have been long sinning, as well as to all others \uc1\u8211* that if I come again, I will spare no one. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}And that will be the proof, which you are looking for, that the Christ speaks through me. There is no weakness in his dealings with you. No, he shows his power among you. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}For though his crucifixion was due to weakness, his life is due to the power of God. And we, also, are weak in his weakness, but with him we will live for you through the power of God. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Put yourselves to the proof, to see whether you are holding to the faith. Test yourselves. Surely you recognise this fact about yourselves \uc1\u8211* that Jesus Christ is in you! Unless indeed you cannot stand the test! {\super\cf2\fs24 6}But I hope that you will recognise that we can stand the test. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}We pray God that you may do nothing wrong, not that we may be seen to stand the test, but that you may do what is right, even though we may seem not to stand the test. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}We have no power at all against the truth, but we have power in the service of the truth. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}We are glad when we are weak, if you are strong. And what we pray for is that you may become perfect. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}This is my reason for writing as I am now doing, while I am away from you, so that, when I am with you, I may not act harshly in the exercise of the authority which the Lord gave me \uc1\u8211* and gave me for building up and not for pulling down.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}And now, friends, goodbye. Aim at perfection; take courage; agree together; live in peace. And then God, the source of all love and peace, will be with you. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Greet one another with a sacred kiss. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}All Christ\uc1\u8217*s people here send you their greetings.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}May the blessing of the Lord Jesus Christ, and the love of God, and the communion with the Holy Spirit, be with you all.
\par}
\sectd\sect{\header \pard\qr\plain\f0\fs16 Galatians (Page \chpgn) \par}{\pard \pagebb
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs60 Paul\uc1\u8217*s Letter to the

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs72 Galatians
 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Introduction

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 1}To the churches in Galatia, from Paul, an apostle whose commission is not from any human authority and is given, not by human beings, but by Jesus Christ and God the Father who raised him from the dead; {\super\cf2\fs24 2}and from all the followers of the Lord here. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}May God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ, bless you and give you peace. For Christ, to rescue us from this present wicked age, {\super\cf2\fs24 4}gave himself for our sins, in accordance with the will of God and Father, {\super\cf2\fs24 5}to whom be ascribed all glory for ever and ever. Amen.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}I am astonished at your so soon deserting him, who called you through the love of Christ, for a different \uc1\u8220*good news,\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}which is really no good news at all. But then, I know that there are people who are harassing you, and who want to pervert the good news of the Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Yet even if we \uc1\u8211* or if an angel from heaven were to tell you any other \uc1\u8220*good news\uc1\u8221* than that which we told you, may he be accursed! {\super\cf2\fs24 9}We have said it before, and I repeat it now \uc1\u8211* If anyone tells you a \uc1\u8220*good news\uc1\u8221* other than that which you received, may he be accursed!
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Is this, I ask, trying to conciliate people, or God? Am I seeking to please people? If I were still trying to please people, I should not be a servant of Christ.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Independence of the Apostle\uc1\u8217*s Gospel

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}I remind you, friends, that the good news which I told is no mere human invention. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}I, at least, did not receive it from any human being, nor was I taught it, but it came to me through a revelation made by Jesus Christ.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}You heard, no doubt, of my conduct when I was devoted to Judaism \uc1\u8211* how I persecuted the church of God to an extent beyond belief, and made havoc of it, {\super\cf2\fs24 14}and how, in my devotion to Judaism, I surpassed many of my contemporaries among my own people in my intense earnestness in upholding the traditions of my ancestors. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}But when God, who had set me apart even before my birth, and who called me by his love, {\super\cf2\fs24 16}saw fit to reveal his Son in me, so that I might tell the good news of him among the Gentiles, then at once, instead of consulting any human being, {\super\cf2\fs24 17}or even going up to Jerusalem to see those who were apostles before me, I went to Arabia, and came back again to Damascus. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}Three years afterwards I went up to Jerusalem to make the acquaintance of Peter, and I stayed a fortnight with him. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}I did not, however, see any other apostle, except James, the Master\uc1\u8217*s brother. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}(As to what I am now writing to you, I call God to witness that I am speaking the truth). {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Afterwards I went to the districts of Syria and Cilicia. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}But I was still unknown even by sight to the Christian churches in Judea; {\super\cf2\fs24 23}all that they had heard was \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*The man who once persecuted us is now telling the good news of the faith of which he once made havoc.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 24}And they praised God for my sake. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 2}Fourteen years afterwards I went up to Jerusalem again with Barnabas, and I took Titus also with me. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}It was in obedience to a revelation that I went; and I laid before the apostles the good news that I am proclaiming among the Gentiles. I did this privately before those who are thought highly of because I was afraid that I might possibly be taking, or might have already taken, a course which would prove useless. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Yet even my companion, Titus, though a Greek, was not compelled to be circumcised. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}But, because of those who pretended to be followers who had stolen in, the intruders who had crept in to spy on the liberty which we have through union with Christ Jesus, in order to bring us back to slavery \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}Why, we did not for a moment yield submission to them, so that the truth of the good news might be yours always! {\super\cf2\fs24 6}Of those who are thought somewhat highly of \uc1\u8211* what they once were makes no difference to me; God does not recognise human distinctions \uc1\u8211* those, I say, who are thought highly of added nothing to my message. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}On the contrary, they saw that I had been entrusted with the good news for the Gentiles, just as Peter had been for the Jews. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}For he who gave Peter power for his mission to the Jews gave me, also, power to go to the Gentiles. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Recognising the charge entrusted to me, James, Peter, and John, who were regarded as pillars of the church, openly acknowledged Barnabas and me as fellow workers, agreeing that we should go to the Gentiles, and they to the Jews. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Only we were to remember the poor \uc1\u8211* the thing I was myself anxious to do. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}But, when Peter came to Antioch, I opposed him to his face; for he stood self-condemned. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Before certain persons came from James, he had been in the habit of eating with the Gentile converts; but, when they came, he began to withdraw and hold aloof, because he was afraid of offending those who still held to circumcision. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}The rest of the Jewish converts were guilty of the same hypocrisy, so that even Barnabas was led away by it. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}But, when I saw that they were not dealing straightforwardly with the truth of the good news, I said to Peter, before them all, \uc1\u8216*If you, who were born a Jew, adopt Gentile customs, instead of Jewish, why are you trying to compel the Gentile converts to adopt Jewish customs?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Law and the Gospel

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}We, though we are Jews by birth and not outcasts of Gentile origin, know that no one is pronounced righteous as the result of obedience to Law, but only through faith in Christ Jesus. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}So we placed our faith in Christ Jesus, in order that we might be pronounced righteous, as the result of faith in Christ, and not of obedience to Law; for such obedience will not result in even one soul\uc1\u8217*s being pronounced righteous. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}If, while seeking to be pronounced righteous through union with Christ, we were ourselves seen to be outcasts, would that make Christ an agent of sin? Heaven forbid! {\super\cf2\fs24 18}For, if I rebuild the things that I pulled down, I prove myself to have done wrong. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}I, indeed, through Law became dead to Law, in order to live for God. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}I have been crucified with Christ. So it is no longer I that live, but it is Christ who lives in me; and, as for my present earthly life, I am living it by faith in the Son of God, who loved me and gave himself for me. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}I do not reject the love of God. If righteousness comes through Law, then there was no need for Christ to die! 
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 3}Foolish Galatians! Who has been fascinating you \uc1\u8211* you before whose eyes Jesus Christ was depicted on the cross? {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Here is the one thing that I want to find out from you \uc1\u8211* Did you receive the Spirit as the result of obedience to Law, or of your having listened with faith? {\super\cf2\fs24 3}Can you be so foolish? After beginning with what is spiritual, do you now end with what is external? {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Did you go through so much to no purpose? \uc1\u8211* if indeed it really was to no purpose! {\super\cf2\fs24 5}He who supplies you abundantly with his Spirit and endows you with such powers \uc1\u8211* does he do this as the result of obedience to Law? Or as the result of your having listened with faith? {\super\cf2\fs24 6}It is just as it was with Abraham \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
he had faith in God, and his faith was regarded by God as righteousness.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}You see, then, that those whose lives are based on faith are the sons of Abraham. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}And scripture, foreseeing that God would pronounce the Gentiles righteous as the result of faith, foretold the good news to Abraham in the words \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Through you all the Gentiles will be blessed.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 9}And, therefore, those whose lives are based on faith share the blessings bestowed on the faith of Abraham. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}All who rely on obedience to Law are under a curse, for scripture says \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Cursed is everyone who does not abide by all that is written in the book of the Law, and do it.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}Again, it is evident that no one is pronounced righteous before God through Law, for we read \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Through faith the righteous will find life.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}But the Law is not based on faith; no, its words are \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Those who practice these precepts will find life through them.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Christ ransomed us from the curse pronounced in the Law, by taking the curse on himself for us, for scripture says \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Cursed is anyone who is hanged on a tree.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And this he did that the blessing given to Abraham might be extended to the Gentiles through their union with Jesus Christ; that so, through our faith, we also might receive the promised gift of the Spirit.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}To take an illustration, friends, from daily life \uc1\u8211* No one sets aside even an agreement between two people, when once it has been confirmed, nor do they add conditions to it. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Now it was to Abraham that the promises were made, \uc1\u8220*and to his offspring.\uc1\u8221* It was not said \uc1\u8220*to his offsprings,\uc1\u8221* as if many persons were meant, but the words were \uc1\u8220*to your offspring,\uc1\u8221* showing that one person was meant \uc1\u8211* and that was Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}My point is this \uc1\u8211* An agreement already confirmed by God cannot be canceled by the Law, which came four hundred and thirty years later, so as to cause the promise to be set aside. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}If our heritage is the result of Law, then it has ceased to be the result of a promise. Yet God conferred it on Abraham by a promise.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 19}What, then, you ask, was the use of the Law? It was a later addition, to make people conscious of their wrong-doings, and intended to last only until the coming of that offspring to whom the promise had been made; and it was delivered through angels by a mediator. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}Now mediation implies more than one person, but God is one only. {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Does that set the Law in opposition to God\uc1\u8217*s promises? Heaven forbid! For, if a Law had been given capable of bestowing life, then righteousness would have actually owed its existence to Law. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}But the words of scripture represent the whole world as being in bondage to sin, so that the promised blessing, dependent, as it is, on faith in Jesus Christ, may be given to those who have faith in him.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Before the coming of faith, we were kept under the guard of the Law, in bondage, awaiting the faith that was destined to be revealed. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}Thus the Law has proved a guide to lead us to Christ, in order that we may be pronounced righteous as the result of faith. {\super\cf2\fs24 25}But now that faith has come we no longer need a guide.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 26}For you are all sons of God, through your faith in Christ Jesus. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}For all of you who were baptized into union with Christ clothed yourselves with Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 28}All distinctions between Jew and Greek, slave and free, male and female, have vanished; for in union with Christ Jesus you are all one. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}And, since you belong to Christ, it follows that you are Abraham\uc1\u8217*s offspring and, under the promise, sharers in the inheritance. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 4}My point is this \uc1\u8211* As long as the heir is under age, there is no difference between him and a slave, though he is master of the whole estate. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}He is subject to the control of guardians and stewards, during the period for which his father has power to appoint them. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}And so is it with us; when we were under age, as it were, we were slaves to the puerile teaching of this world; {\super\cf2\fs24 4}but, when the full time came, God sent his Son \uc1\u8211* born a woman\uc1\u8217*s child, born subject to Law \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 5}To ransom those who were subject to Law, so that we might take our position as sons.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 6}And it is because you are sons that God sent into our hearts the Spirit of his Son, with the cry \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Abba, our Father.\uc1\u8221* {\super\cf2\fs24 7}You, therefore, are no longer a slave, but a son; and, if a son, then an heir also, by God\uc1\u8217*s appointment.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 8}Yet formerly, in your ignorance of God, you became slaves to \uc1\u8220*gods\uc1\u8221* which were no gods. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}But now that you have found God \uc1\u8211* or, rather, have been found by him \uc1\u8211* how is it that you are turning back to that poor and feeble puerile teaching, to which yet once again you are wanting to become slaves? {\super\cf2\fs24 10}You are scrupulous in keeping days and months and seasons and years! {\super\cf2\fs24 11}You make me fear that the labour which I have spent on you may have been wasted.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 12}I entreat you, friends, to become like me, as I became like you. You have never done me any wrong. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}You remember that it was owing to bodily infirmity that on the first occasion I told you the good news. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}And as for what must have tried you in my condition, it did not inspire you with scorn or disgust, but you welcomed me as if I had been an angel of God \uc1\u8211* or Christ Jesus himself! {\super\cf2\fs24 15}What has become then, of your blessings? For I can bear witness that, had it been possible, you would have torn out your eyes and given them to me! {\super\cf2\fs24 16}Am I to think, then, that I have become your enemy by telling you the truth? {\super\cf2\fs24 17}Certain people are seeking your favour, but with no honourable object. No, indeed, they want to isolate you, so that you will have to seek their favour. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}It is always honourable to have your favour sought in an honourable cause, and not only when I am with you, my dear children \uc1\u8211* {\super\cf2\fs24 19}you for whom I am again enduring a mother\uc1\u8217*s pains, until a likeness to Christ will have been formed in you. {\super\cf2\fs24 20}But I could wish to be with you now and speak in a different tone, for I am perplexed about you.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 21}Tell me, you who want to be still subject to Law \uc1\u8211* Why don\uc1\u8217*t you listen to the Law? {\super\cf2\fs24 22}Scripture says that Abraham had two sons, one the child of the slave-woman and the other the child of the free woman. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}But the child of the slave-woman was born in the course of nature, while the child of the free woman was born in fulfilment of a promise. {\super\cf2\fs24 24}This story may be taken as an allegory. The women stand for two Covenants. One covenant, given from Mount Sinai, produces a race of slaves and is represented by Hagar {\super\cf2\fs24 25}(The word Hagar meaning in Arabia Mount Sinai) and it ranks with the Jerusalem of today, for she and her children are in slavery. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}But the Jerusalem above is free, and she it is who is our mother. {\super\cf2\fs24 27}For scripture says \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Rejoice, you barren one, who does never bear,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
Break into shouts, you who are never in labour,
\par}

{\pard\fi-2080\li2800
For many are the children of her who is desolate \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-1720\li2800
aye, more than of her who has a husband.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 28}As for ourselves, friends, we, like Isaac, are children born in fulfilment of a promise. {\super\cf2\fs24 29}Yet at that time the child born in the course of nature persecuted the child born by the power of the Spirit; and it is the same now. {\super\cf2\fs24 30}But what does the passage of scripture say?
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Send away the slave-woman and her son; for the slave\uc1\u8217*s son will not be coheir with the son of the free woman.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 31}And so, friends, we are not children of a slave, but of her who is free. 
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Gospel in the Daily Life

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\cf1 5}It is for freedom that Christ set us free; stand firm therefore, and do not again be held under the yoke of slavery.
\par}

{\pard 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Understand that I, Paul, myself tell you that if you allow yourselves to be circumcised, Christ will avail you nothing. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}I again declare to everyone who receives circumcision, that he binds himself to obey the whole Law. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}You have severed yourselves from Christ \uc1\u8211* you who are seeking to be pronounced righteous through Law; you have fallen away from love. {\super\cf2\fs24 5}For we, by the help of the Spirit, are eagerly waiting for the fulfilment of our hope \uc1\u8211* that we may be pronounced righteous as the result of faith. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}If we are in union with Christ Jesus, neither is circumcision nor the omission of it anything, but faith, working through love, is everything. {\super\cf2\fs24 7}You were once making good progress! Who has hindered you from obeying the truth? {\super\cf2\fs24 8}The persuasion brought to bear on you does not come from him who calls you. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}A little leaven leavens all the dough. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}I, through my union with the Lord, am persuaded that you will learn to think with me. But the man who is disturbing your minds will have to bear his punishment, whoever he may be. {\super\cf2\fs24 11}If I, friends, am still proclaiming circumcision, why am I still persecuted? It seems that the cross has ceased to be an obstacle! {\super\cf2\fs24 12}I could even wish that the people who are unsettling you would go further still and mutilate themselves.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Remember, friends, to you the call came to give you freedom. Only do not make your freedom an opportunity for self-indulgence, but serve one another in a loving spirit. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}Indeed, the whole Law has been summed up in this one precept \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*You must love your neighbour as you love yourself.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 15}But, if you are continually wounding and preying on one another, take care that you are not destroyed by one another.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 16}This is what I have to say \uc1\u8211* Let your steps be guided by the Spirit, and then you will never gratify the cravings of your earthly nature. {\super\cf2\fs24 17}For these cravings of our earthly nature conflict with the Spirit, and the Spirit with our earthly nature \uc1\u8211* they are two contrary principles \uc1\u8211* so that you cannot do what you wish. {\super\cf2\fs24 18}But, if you follow the guidance of the Spirit, you are not subject to Law. {\super\cf2\fs24 19}The sins of our earthly nature are unmistakable. They are sins like these \uc1\u8211* sexual immorality, impurity, indecency, {\super\cf2\fs24 20}idolatry, sorcery, quarrels, strife, jealousy, outbursts of passion, rivalries, dissensions, divisions, {\super\cf2\fs24 21}feelings of envy, drunkenness, revelry, and the like. And I warn you, as I warned you before, that those who indulge in such things will have no place in the kingdom of God. {\super\cf2\fs24 22}But the fruit produced by the Spirit is love, joy, peace, forbearance, kindliness, generosity, trustfulness, gentleness, self-control. {\super\cf2\fs24 23}Against such things there is no law! {\super\cf2\fs24 24}And those who belong to Jesus, the Christ, have already crucified their earthly nature, with its passions and its cravings.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 25}Since our life is due to the Spirit, let us rule our conduct also by the Spirit. {\super\cf2\fs24 26}Do not let us grow vain, and provoke or envy one another.  {\cf1 6}My friends, even if someone should be caught committing a sin, you who are spiritually minded should, in a gentle spirit, help them to recover themselves, taking care that you yourselves are not tempted. {\super\cf2\fs24 2}Bear one another\uc1\u8217*s burdens, and so carry out the Law of the Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 3}If a person imagines themselves to be somebody, when they are really nobody, they deceive themselves. {\super\cf2\fs24 4}Let everyone test their own work, and then their cause for satisfaction will be in themselves and not in a comparison with their neighbour; {\super\cf2\fs24 5}for everyone must bear their own load. {\super\cf2\fs24 6}The person, however, who is being instructed in the message ought always to share their blessings with their teacher.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 7}Do not be deceived. God cannot be mocked. What a person sows that they will reap. {\super\cf2\fs24 8}For the person who sows the field of their earthly nature will from that earthly nature reap corruption; while the one who sows the field of the spirit will from that spirit reap eternal life. {\super\cf2\fs24 9}Let us never tire of doing right, for at the proper season we will reap our harvest, if we do not grow weary. {\super\cf2\fs24 10}Therefore, I say, as the opportunity occurs, let us treat everyone with kindness, and especially members of the Household of the faith.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 Conclusion in the Apostle\uc1\u8217*s own handwriting

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 11}See in what large letters I am writing with my own hand. {\super\cf2\fs24 12}Those who wish to appear to advantage in regard to outward observances are the people who are trying to compel you to be circumcised; and they do it only to avoid being persecuted for the cross of Jesus, the Christ. {\super\cf2\fs24 13}Even these men who are circumcised do not themselves keep the Law; yet they want you to be circumcised, so that they may boast of your observance of the rite. {\super\cf2\fs24 14}But, for my part, may I never boast of anything except the cross of Jesus Christ, our Master, through whom the world has been crucified to me, and I to the world. {\super\cf2\fs24 15}For neither is circumcision nor the omission of it anything; but a new nature is everything. {\super\cf2\fs24 16}May all who rule their conduct by this principle find peace and mercy \uc1\u8211* they who are the Israel of God.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 17}For the future let no one trouble me; for I bear the marks of Jesus branded on my body.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi720 
 {\super\cf2\fs24 18}May the blessing of Jesus Christ, our Lord, rest on your souls, friends. Amen.
\par}
